$ Windows code pages

? A *code page* maps the numbers 0 through 255 to a character.

In → Windows/dirs/Windows/System32/cmd_exe[cmd.exe] (or another → Windows/dirs/Windows/System32/conhost_exe[`conhost.exe`] based application), text is written or read using
the currently specified code page.
-
The current code page can be displayed or changed with → Windows/dirs/Windows/System32/chcp_com[`chcp`] and → Windows/dirs/Windows/System32/mode_com[`mode con: cp`].


There are two groups of → Windows code pages:
  • OEM: used by *console applications* (→ Windows/dirs/Windows/System32/conhost_exe[console host]?)
  • ANSI (which is a misnomer and is officially called *Windows code pages*)

The code page for → development/Unicode/UTF-8 is 65001.

sa:

  A list of code pages can be displayed with the → Microsoft/dot-net method → Microsoft/dot-net/namespaces-classes/System/Text/Encoding#system-text-encoding-GetEncodings[`System.Text.Encoding.GetEncodings()`].
  -
  A specific encoding is returned by → Microsoft/dot-net/namespaces-classes/System/Text/Encoding/Get/Encoding[`System.Text.Encoding::GetEncoding()`].

  → Windows/development/code-page/byte-2-char[byte-2-char.c] is a simple C program that converts the bytes between 128 and 255 to selected code pages and the
  write an → development/web/HTML/tags/table[HTML table].


  The `C_codepage.NLS` files under → Windows/dirs/Windows/System32

  The original IBM PC's codepage was → Windows/development/code-page/437[437].

  → Windows/registry[Registry] key → Windows/registry/tree/HKEY_CLASSES_ROOT/MIME/Database/Codepage[`HKEY_CLASSES_ROOT\MIME\Database\Codepage`]

  the → Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/noun/file/out#ps-out-file-encoding[`-encoding`] parameter of the → Windows/PowerShell cmdlet
  → Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/noun/file/out[`out-file`].

  → development/Unicode/character-encoding
